{{Unreferenced stub|auto=yes|date=December 2009}} {{Infobox Protected area | name = Gerald Durrell Endemic Wildlife Sanctuary | iucn_category = IV | map = Mauritius | relief = yes | map_width = 220 | map_caption = Map of [[Mauritius]] | location = [[Black River District, Mauritius]] | nearest_city = [[Chamarel]] | coordinates = {{coords|20|25|S|57|20|E|display=inline, title}} | area = NA | established = 1984 | visitation_num = Visitors not allowed except with rangers | visitation_year = 2005 | governing_body = [[Mauritian Wildlife Foundation]] }}
The '''Gerald Durrell Endemic Wildlife Sanctuary''' is an [[animal sanctuary]] founded in 1984, in Western [[Mauritius]]. It is an area closed off to the public, in the [[Black River District, Mauritius|Black River Gorge]] region, which is densely forested, and is used for breeding rare, [[endemic (ecology)|endemic]] Mauritian species. Among the endangered species in the sanctuary is the [[Indian Ocean kestrels|Mauritius kestrel]], once the rarest bird in the world with only 4 members left. It has been successfully bred and the population has now reached the capacity of Mauritius.
The sanctuary is named after [[natural history|naturalist]] [[Gerald Durrell]], who was associated with Mauritius' conservation movement from its inception in the 1970s, and who adopted the extinct Mauritian [[dodo]] as the logo for his ''Jersey Wildlife Preservation Trust'', now [[Durrell Wildlife Conservation Trust]].
The sanctuary is run jointly by the National Parks and Conservation Service and [[Mauritian Wildlife Foundation]], with the help of the ''Durrell Wildlife Conservation Trust''.
